  "text": "As for the effects of additional gene flow, negative admixture estimates accompanied by large standard deviations are commonly observed when more complex exchanges occurred than a simple admixture event, or when the parental populations are improperly chosen [CITATION_1] . We showed that replacing our four parental populations with other, implausible parental populations leads to evidently implausible results (table 5) . On the contrary, most values estimated using what we consider plausible parental populations were in the range 0%-100%, and standard errors were always below 15%. Therefore, by and large these results do not suggest that the admixture model we chose grossly misrepresents the population processes leading to the current European genetic diversity.",
